#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:1
msgid "Start Date: 2014-12-06"
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:2
msgid ""
"RFC PR: [rust-lang/rfcs#501](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/501)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:3
msgid ""
"Rust Issue: [rust-lang/rust#20561](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/"
"issues/20561)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:5
msgid "Summary"
msgstr "摘要"

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:7
msgid ""
"Make name and behavior of the `#![no_std]` and `#![no_implicit_prelude]` "
"attributes consistent by renaming the latter to `#![no_prelude]` and having "
"it only apply to the current module."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:11
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr "動機"

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:13
msgid ""
"Currently, Rust automatically inserts an implicit `extern crate std;` in the "
"crate root that can be disabled with the `#[no_std]` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:16
msgid ""
"It also automatically inserts an implicit `use std::prelude::*;` in every "
"module that can be disabled with the `#[no_implicit_prelude]` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:19
msgid ""
"Lastly, if `#[no_std]` is used, all module automatically don't import the "
"prelude, so the `#[no_implicit_prelude]` attribute is unneeded in those "
"cases."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:22
msgid ""
"However, the later attribute is inconsistent with the former in two regards:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:24
msgid "Naming wise, it redundantly contains the word \"implicit\""
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:25
msgid "Semantic wise, it applies to the current module **and all submodules**."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:27
msgid ""
"That last one is surprising because normally, whether or not a module "
"contains a certain import does not affect whether or not a sub module "
"contains a certain import, so you'd expect a attribute that disables an "
"implicit import to only apply to that module as well."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:31
msgid ""
"This behavior also gets in the way in some of the already rare cases where "
"you want to disable the prelude while still linking to std."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:34
msgid ""
"As an example, the author had been made aware of this behavior of "
"`#[no_implicit_prelude]` while attempting to prototype a variation of the "
"`Iterator` traits, leading to code that looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:41
msgid "/* ... */"
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:44
msgid "/* Tries to access the existing prelude, and fails to resolve */"
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:49
msgid ""
"While such use cases might be resolved by just requiring an explicit `use "
"std::prelude::*;` in the submodules, it seems like just making the attribute "
"behave as expected is the better outcome."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:52
msgid ""
"Of course, for the cases where you want the prelude disabled for a whole sub "
"tree of modules, it would now become necessary to add a `#[no_prelude]` "
"attribute in each of them - but that is consistent with imports in general."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:56
msgid "Detailed design"
msgstr "詳細設計"

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:58
msgid ""
"`libsyntax` needs to be changed to accept both the name "
"`no_implicit_prelude` and `no_prelude` for the attribute. Then the "
"attributes effect on the AST needs to be changed to not deeply remove all "
"imports, and all fallout of this change needs to be fixed in order for the "
"new semantic to bootstrap."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:63
msgid ""
"Then a snapshot needs to be made, and all uses of `#[no_implicit_prelude]` "
"can be changed to `#[no_prelude]` in both the main code base, and user code."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:66
msgid ""
"Finally, the old attribute name should emit a deprecated warning, and be "
"removed in time."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:68
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:70
msgid ""
"The attribute is a rare use case to begin with, so any effort put into this "
"would distract from more important stabilization work."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:73
msgid "Alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:75
msgid "Keep the current behavior"
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:76
msgid ""
"Remove the `#[no_implicit_prelude]` attribute all together, instead forcing "
"users to use `#[no_std]` in combination with `extern crate std;` and `use "
"std::prelude::*`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0501-consistent_no_prelude_attributes.md:78
msgid ""
"Generalize preludes more to allow custom ones, which might supersede the "
"attributes from this RFC."
msgstr ""
